05395nam a22009015i 9783110685046DE-B159720230228015514.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106850467 a10.1515/97831106850462doi  a(DE-B1597)539755  a(OCoLC)1198930456  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aPHI0040002bisacsh1 aMitchell, Sam, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFault-Tracing: Against Quine-Duhem :bA Defense of the Objectivity of Scientific Justification /cSam Mitchell. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VIII, 224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEpistemic Studies : Philosophy of Science, Cognition and Mind ,x2512-5168 ;v4000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1. An Example of a Constructive Tree in Darwin -- t2. The Meaning of Independent Confirmation -- t3. How to Confirm Hypotheses about Unobservables -- t4. Fault Tracing -- t5. Examples of Fault Tracing -- t6. Chang’s Paradox -- t7. Escaping Cycles of Confirmation -- t8. The Theory-Ladenness of Observation -- t9. Cycles of Observations -- t10. Van Fraassen’s Paradox 10.1515/9783110685046-011 -- t11. Human Values Are Irrelevant to Empirical Justification -- t12. From Constructivism to Metaphysics: Potential Applications -- tBibliography -- tName Index -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is widely believed in philosophy of science that nobody can claim that any verdict of science is forced upon us by the effects of a physical world upon our sense organs and instruments. The Quine-Duhem problem supposedly allows us to resist any conclusion. Views on language aside, Quine is supposed to have shown this decisively. But it is just false. In many scientific examples, there is simply no room to doubt that a particular hypothesis is responsible for a refutation or established by the observations. Fault Tracing shows how to play independently established hypotheses against each other to determine whether an arbitrary hypothesis needs to be altered in the light of (apparently) refuting evidence. It analyses real examples from natural science, as well as simpler cases. It argues that, when scientific theories have a structure that prevents them from using this method, the theory looks wrong, and is subject to serious criticism. This is a new, and potentially far-reaching, theory of empirical justification.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aDuhem. 4aQuine. 4aWissenschaftliche Objektivität. 4aWissenschaftliche Rechtfertigung. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Epistemology.2bisacsh  aQuine-Duhem.  aconfirmation.  ascientific justification.  ascientific objectivity.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2020z978311069628808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2020 Part 1z978311069627108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCz978311065906108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020 Englishz978311070482208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Philosophy 2020z9783110704648oZDB-23-DPH0 cEPUBz97831106850910 cprintz978311068499540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311068504640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110685046423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110685046/original  a978-3-11-065906-1  De Gruyter English eBooks 2020 - UCb2020  a978-3-11-06